Title
The Between-Session Gap in Executive Coaching

Working Title Variant
Why Coaching Outcomes Break Down Between Sessions

Central Thesis
Executive coaching outcomes are usually judged by session quality, but leadership risk accumulates between sessions. The critical failure point is not insight generation inside the conversation; it is execution continuity in the days that follow. Organizations can improve coaching impact by operationalizing three between-session disciplines: signal tracking, pre-conversation preparation, and accountability loops.

Why This Matters Now
Senior leaders are making higher-stakes decisions at faster intervals under greater informational load. In this environment, even strong coaching conversations fail to translate into measurable outcomes if leaders do not have repeatable between-session operating routines. This creates a hidden ROI leak in coaching investments.

What Is New
The article reframes coaching effectiveness from session-centric quality to between-session execution continuity. Rather than adding coaching hours, it introduces lightweight operating mechanisms that increase follow-through quality and decision readiness.

Core Argument Structure
1) The mismatch: where organizations evaluate coaching versus where risk actually forms.
2) The mechanism: why preparation decay, signal blindness, and weak commitment design reduce outcomes.
3) The operating model: a practical, three-discipline framework leaders and coaches can implement immediately.
4) The measurement shift: what to track to evaluate true coaching impact.

The Three Between-Session Disciplines
1. Signal tracking
Define and monitor a small set of role-critical signals (internal stakeholder, external market, team, and role-transition indicators).

2. Preparation protocol
Before high-stakes conversations, require a short prep brief covering objective, audience map, narrative, likely objections, and decision request.

3. Accountability loops
Convert coaching commitments into explicit actions, owners, checkpoints, and review cadence.

Implementation Blueprint (30 Days)
Week 1: Select 5-7 role-critical signals and establish tracking cadence.
Week 2: Introduce a one-page pre-conversation brief template for key meetings.
Week 3: Move from generic action items to explicit commitment contracts with due dates and evidence of completion.
Week 4: Review outcomes with coach and manager; refine signals and prep protocol.

Measures of Success
- Preparation quality trend before key conversations
- Commitment completion rate
- Decision velocity in priority initiatives
- Stakeholder confidence indicators
- Reduction in repeated context reset during coaching sessions

Audience
Senior leaders, CHRO and talent leaders, executive coaches, and business unit leaders accountable for leadership performance.

Estimated Length
1,800 to 2,200 words.

Proposed Author Bio
Rich Rothschild is founder of Starting Monday, an executive-readiness platform that helps coaches and senior executives improve preparation quality, signal visibility, and between-session follow-through.

Submission Note
The article is non-promotional, practitioner-focused, and evidence-backed. It includes limitations and distinguishes observed correlations from causal claims.